         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1122">
               <p>Ireland began his career in <placeName>Bristol</placeName> as a shopman, prospered
                  as a sugar merchant, and eventually owned an estate in
                     <placeName>Brislington</placeName>. He was an evangelical sympathizer. In <date
                     when="1749-10">October 1749</date> he married <persName>Constant
                     Norman</persName>, daughter of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1513.xml"
                     />John</persName> and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1514.xml"/>Mary
                     (Oxford) Norman</persName>—owners of the brickyard on St. Philip&apos;s Plain
                  in <placeName>Bristol</placeName>, where <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> preached his first sermon in
                  the open air on <date when="1739-04-02">Apr. 2, 1739</date>. Ireland was
                  particularly close to <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0719.xml"/>John
                     Fletcher</persName><!-- I am unsure if this is the specific Rev. John fletcher but tagged it just in case -->,
                  who preached the funeral sermon for Ireland&apos;s wife
                     <persName>Constant</persName> in <date when="1769">1769</date>.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
